column2: Fermentation and harvest conditions of Lactobacillus delbrueckii subsp. bulgaricus CFL1
Biological replicate = biologically distinct samples produced by independent fermentations
Harvest times for functional properties measurements (culturability and acidifying activity): th1, th2 and th3

column3: time of harvest 1 = at the mid-exponential growth phase
time of harvest 2 = at the deceleration growth phase
time of harvest 3 = at the stationary growth phase
additional harvest times for measurements carried out throughout fermentation (OD, gluc, LA, DCW)

column2: Technical repetition: different measurements on the same sample
t: time (h);  0 h = inoculation of the bioreactor
OD: optical density measured continously at 880 nm and after sampling at 600 nm
NaOH:  mL of a 4.25 M (mol/L) NaOH solution added into the bioreactor by a peristaltic pump during the fermentation to maintain the pH at the set value
The density of the NaOH solution at 4.25 M is 1.2192 g/mL (measurement carried out using a pycnometer).
gluc: glucose concentration (g/L) measured by HPLC after sampling
LA: lactic acid concentration (g/L) measured by HPLC after sampling
DCW: dry cell weight concentration (g/L) measured after sampling; drying conditions: 80 degrees Celsius for 24 h
Each fermentation condition: A, B, C, and D with its respective biological replicate (1, 2 or 3) is organized in columns.
Each fermentation condition has at least three biological replicates.
The data per fermentation condition and biological replicate are organized as follows:
(i) First columns contain the data acquisition of fermentation parameters (T, pH, OD at 880 nm, and NaOH addition) throughout the bacterial growth.
(ii) The following columns contain the measurements that were carried out after sampling (a_th) and harvesting (th1, th2, and th3) from the bioreactor: OD at 600 nm, DCW, gluc, LA.
The data organization is summarized here below:

column193: Only for this fermentation condition and biological replicate, the NaOH solution addition was monitored by the weight loss the NaOH solution consumption.
The NaOH solution was placed on an analytical balance, monitoring its weight every two minutes during the growth (Balance software, INRAE, Thiverval-Grignon, France).
To convert the units of grams to mL, we divided the mass in grams of NaOH solution at 4.25 M by its density (1.2192 g/mL). This density was measured by a pycnometer.
time for T, pH, and OD at 880nm
